		<exercise lesson="2" section="2" type="title">
			<title>Web site development principles:</title>
		</exercise>
		<exercise lesson="2" section="2" type="paragraph">
			<paragraph>Before you create a Web site, you must first create a #Input#.</paragraph>
		</exercise>
		<exercise lesson="2" section="2" type="paragraph">
			<paragraph>Successful Web sites have a strong, central #Input# aimed at a distinct #Input#.</paragraph>
		</exercise>
		<exercise lesson="2" section="2" type="paragraph">
			<paragraph>Because the design elements with which you display information on your site are important, you should #Input# your site on a regular basis as it is being developed.</paragraph>
		</exercise>
		<exercise lesson="2" section="2" type="paragraph">
			<paragraph>When creating a Web site, #Input# are relevant organization employees or contributors who can help determine the purpose of the Web site, the site's look and feel, the services that the audience requires from the site, and so forth.</paragraph>
		</exercise>
		<exercise lesson="2" section="2" type="paragraph">
			<paragraph>
				As you communicate your Web site plan to relevant parties, consider using #Input# to help illustrate your plan.
			</paragraph>
		</exercise>
		<exercise lesson="2" section="2" type="paragraph">
			<paragraph>As you develop Web pages, make sure that you #Input# your Web pages using multiple Web browsers.</paragraph>
		</exercise>
		<exercise lesson="2" section="2" type="paragraph">
			<paragraph>
				As a general rule, the closer you adhere to #Input#, the more consistently your Web pages will render in various browsers.
			</paragraph>
		</exercise>
		<exercise lesson="2" section="2" type="paragraph">
			<paragraph>
				Once your site is live, your Web team will receive various kinds of #Input# from customers and stakeholders.
